    "summarizer": {
      "general_reader_takeaway": "This paper from MIT claims that quantum wave functions can be derived exactly from classical particle paths alone \u2014 no Feynman \"sum over all histories\" needed \u2014 by combining multi-valued classical action solutions with classical fluid density. The review board found the individual examples correct but the central proof fatally flawed: it silently assumes a condition that does not hold in general, and the paper's treatment of the Bell inequality experiment substitutes continuous spinor math for the discrete binary measurements that Bell's theorem actually governs. All worked examples succeed for reasons already known to physics, not because the general framework is valid.",
      "reviewer": "claude",
      "technical_takeaway": "The central proof (Lemma 1) requires the Eulerian spatial gradient of the classical density \u03c1_k to vanish \u2014 which eliminates the Bohm quantum potential Q = \u2212(\u210f\u00b2/2m)(\u2207\u00b2\u221a\u03c1_k / \u221a\u03c1_k) and recovers the classical Hamilton-Jacobi equation from the Schr\u00f6dinger equation \u2014 but this condition is neither stated as a hypothesis nor generally true. All three reviewers independently identified this as a fatal gap across both review cycles. The paper conflates Lagrangian path density (a scalar along a trajectory, no x-dependence by construction) with Eulerian density field (a function of x and t), and every worked example succeeds because Q = 0 coincidentally holds in that case: spherical-wave 1/r\u00b2 density in 3D (\u2207\u00b2(1/r) = 0), quadratic Hamiltonians (Feynman-exact by prior work), and Coulomb via the Duru\u2013Kleinert mapping to the harmonic oscillator. No example with a general anharmonic potential is provided. The EPR/Bell section computes correlations of continuous spinor projections before binary quantization \u2014 which avoids Bell's theorem rather than refuting it. All relativistic extensions inherit the unestablished base lemma."
    }
